Parliament did not support an amendment to free Tymoshenko
The Ukrainian Parliament has rejected today the proposal to repeal the amendment to the section of the Criminal Code condemning opposition leader Yulia Tymoshenko.
The amendment would open the door to the ex-prime minister's release, but parliamentarians rejected the proposal to reduce penalties for economic crimes in the second reading.
In October, Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison for allegedly signing a deal with Russia disadvantageous to Ukraine on the purchase of natural gas.
The verdict is not yet firm, the appeals court is obliged to review it in December.
Tymoshenko was convinced that this was a political revenge of the regime, and even in the West doubts have arisen about the impartiality of the court.
The proposal to remove paragraph 365 of the Penal Code condemning the former prime minister was supported by 147 deputies in the vote.
226 votes were required for approval.
