Daily menu of an obese child: no breakfast and dinner sausages
More than a third of children between the ages of 9 and 13 have overweight problems, where overweight affects 9% of the school population and obesity 5%.
Obese children mostly come from families with an unhealthy lifestyle, according to current research.
It is again demonstrated the importance of the environment where it grows for the healthy development of the person, as well as the models that serve as a reference.
At the table, obsessed children are fed, for example, sausages at least twice as often as children from normal-weight families.
For dinner, more than 19% of obese people had eaten fries the day before the analysis, which is linked to the “Obesity is not a coincidence” prevention program.
In families of overweight children there is no habit of doing sports, which is applicable to most current families, where only 15% of children responded that their parents, at least once a week, find time for physical exercise.
A survey of 900 children
The survey was conducted at the end of last school year and involved nearly 900 elementary school children from all over the Czech Republic.
It was already the second edition of the program "Obesity is not a coincidence", which is supported by the General Health Insurance Company and the company Unilever.
So far, more than 12,000 children have participated in the project from the 4th to the 8th grade.
A proper diet and plenty of exercise in the family are determining factors, which significantly reduce the number of overweight and even obese children.
“Only half of the children surveyed have responded that they have five meals per day on a diet: breakfast, lunch, food, snack and dinner, which is one of the basic conditions for a healthy diet,” one of the survey’s findings says.
No breakfast but with sausage for dinner
Specialists warn that, in a healthy development, the details, which also count, are important, such as having a fixed time for breakfast with the family.
In the Czech Republic, however, only 23% of school families eat breakfast at the same time.
In most families, each one eats breakfast alone.
But the worst thing was to find out that in 10% of households you don’t have breakfast at all.
Breakfast, however, is the basis of a correct daily diet.
The study shows that in families of obese children, insane fries are consumed much more often.
Almost everyone – regardless of weight – drinks sweet refreshments daily (70%).
As a rule, more than 40% of the children surveyed do sports, however, among their parents this result is reduced to less than half, only 15%.
Make your own diet
The next phase of the study allowed the chosen boys (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to create their own diets from all possible offers according to their tastes and opinions.
"The dietary preferences of Czech children aged 12 to 15, from the point of view of healthy eating, are far from ideal."
Among his favorite foods are pasta, meat and sweets.
“The popularity of sweet soda is especially alarming,” the study’s final report warns.
As the main food, the pasta is carried by the palm and the poultry meat is followed closely.
Practically, children always reject legumes and the taste for fish and vegetables is very low.
Changing to Healthy Habits
At the same time, the study shows that children are willing to change their eating habits if they receive the right information.
“In the control group of study participants, who completed the questionnaire after completing the ‘Obesity is not a coincidence’ prevention program, there was in many cases a significant change in favor of the principles of healthy eating,” the study’s findings point out.
Pay attention, for example, to sweet soft drinks, where many children would start to prefer normal and flowing water.
Children would also more often choose poultry meat and fish for the main meal in the questionnaire and restrict the consumption of sweet foods and flour derivatives.
