IBM History: From Cheese Cutter to Space Flight
The company IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York a hundred years ago, its original name being Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM was adopted as early as 1924 - it was originally a brand used in branches in Canada and South America.
The foundation that gave rise to IBM arises from the merger of four companies dating back to the 1880s.
He possessed inventions such as the famous "touch clock", which allows him to control the incoming and outgoing of employees.
The architect of the new company was businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who until 1930 also chaired its supervisory board.
Flint hired Thomas J. Watson, the head of a competition company, to help him manage the company.
The new leader overshadowed the founder of IBM (Watson’s ideas remain the firm foundation on which corporate culture and identity are based).
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name implies, began with the production and sale of all kinds of business appliances, from meat and cheese cutters to cash registers.
During the first four years Watson led the company, revenue doubled by $9 million and began the company’s great expansion across the continents.
Watson was so crucial to the company that, after nearly forty years in the chair of the boss, he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began working on the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, IBM staff and computers helped NASA guide flights to space (to Mercury, Saturn, and in 1969 the famous flight to the Moon).
In 1964, IBM developed the first generation of computers, the IBM System/360 series.
The classic "pieces", which established the computer standard of the time, came to the market under the name IBM 5150 in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, which, in turn, acquired the consulting part of the company Pricewaterhouse Coopers and began to offer full advice and high value-added services.
The strategy that IBM has paid for over the past three years is the Smarter Planet concept, i.e., “a smarter planet.”
Its aim is to make more rational use of technology, although the areas have not yet been planned or the circumstances have improved, for example, in terms of transport and city administration.
For the trading sector, IBM recently introduced the “Smart Commerce” platform that allows retailers to manage the entire trading cycle.
IBM has a long history in this country.
Already in 1932 he opened a branch in Czechoslovakia at the time, the first country to have it in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, IBM <0xC4><0x8C>R also operates the strategic outsourcing centre in Brno.
