How travel prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five authorized state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia at the time: <0xC4><0x8C>edok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
The travel agencies of the time sold travel in most cases only to the socialist bloc, as travel to the West was very restricted.
Czech tourists therefore went on holiday to the beaches of the GDR (German Democratic Republic), to the Soviet Union (Sochi in the Crimea on the Black Sea) to Bulgaria and Romania (both in the Black Sea) and to Hungary (Balaton).
A positive exception was the period between 1962 and 1972, when it was possible to travel to Yugoslavia, however, after the Yugoslav regime leaned westward and the travels of Czech tourists were then quite restricted.
A great paradox of socialism was the fact that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e., also the Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely and individually even through the socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter, if not, individual travel was not possible.
Travel agencies at the time also offered trips to the West, but one had to line up with a sleeping bag and spend the night, or have "good acquaintances" in the agency.
But not everything was earned.
The so-called "promise of change" which was the condition for travel to the West, was not granted to the "politically unreliable people", who thus could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency and, without a guarantee of exchange, it was not possible to obtain the resources (the Western currency) to travel to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs spent their holidays in their own country, so there were a large number of cottages and summer houses, which the Czechs bought. This custom still persists.
The way the Czechs travelled has undergone a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 for us it was not going to spend the holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria, last year the Czechs made 4.5 million holiday trips to countries around the world.
It is a great paradox, of which we are no longer aware today, the fact that the currently favorite destination, Croatia, until 1989 could not travel freely, because it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
In the early 1990s, visa-free travel to neighbouring Western European states was imposed, causing a huge surge of short-term visits, especially to Vienna or Germany.
The Czechoslovaks, for a long time, were not tired of the excursions to the West, everyone wanted to see it at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris, groups of Czechs slept in parks in tents, as our income at the time did not allow us to pay for a hotel or pension.
A typical feature of the Czechs of that time was to take food (canned food, sausages, etc.) with you to save.
Another important moment was the introduction of the convertibility of the Czech crown, so our tourists could finally, after decades, freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living was increasing and with it also the average wages, which caused an increase in demand for travel around 1997.
With the increase in travel demand, agencies began, starting in 1997, to regularly prepare trips using charter flights connections, which made travel prices incredibly lower compared to the past, thanks to the possibility of getting discounts on the volume of passengers.
By the late 1990s, the Czechs were already traveling visa-free to almost all developed countries except the US, which further simplified our travels.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary tourism happened already in 2000, when the first direct flight from the Czech Republic to an exotic country was organized, thanks to a huge demand, and went to Thailand.
Since that year, direct charter flights depart every year with Czech tourists to distant and hot countries. This winter you will fly directly from the Czech Republic to 12 exotic destinations.
The exotic countries are currently visited by about 100,000 Czechs a year.
Another interesting moment of this era, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the U.S. abolished visas for Czech tourists, making our country one of the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, Czechs, for the first time in their history, have spent more than half of their vacation abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, have spent more than 15,000 Czech crowns per head on travel abroad, including on-site expenses.
