With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three pieces of content a day, Facebook’s “data supernova” is generating a boom in research, boosting the number of academic papers with the site’s name in the title to nearly 800% in the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that it allows you to study people you couldn’t approach with a folder on the street.
"Before, when you were trying to survey people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
“You would have to go through the game, and they would never allow you access,” Bartlett says.
"Facebook deletes all that - you go to them directly."
Others say the site could provide a way to identify and address health-social issues.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin-Madison and colleagues found that college students who talked about their drunkenness feats on Facebook had a significantly higher risk of drinking problems than students who remained silent on the subject.
Moreno suggests that fellow students, such as residential counselors, could control the site and intervene to help a student post too many status updates with their drunks.
"You can't treat a problem if you can't diagnose it," said Dimitri Christakis, Moreno's co-author and director of the Center for Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Seattle Children's Research Institute, the Washington Post said.
“We have found a way to identify at-risk children who would otherwise not be diagnosed.”
Facebook is also constantly “pinching” its own population to get data.
The site's Data Team has compiled statistics on the state of the relationship and Valentine's Day, the expectation of electoral participation in the mid-2010 legislative period, and a National Happiness Index (mainly using the information that can be accessed - digital freedom advocates long ago who argue that the site should provide other amount of research).
However, Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not – the sacrifice of being able to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away is allowing the site to mine your personal information.
But what happens when Facebook users become part of a survey they don’t even know about?
While researchers have well-defined guidelines on how to collect your data offline, online is a free bar for everyone.
“I don’t think many of the users have even thought about the fact that a researcher might be examining their profiles,” says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Laboratory, about a 2006 study he conducted with students’ Facebook public walls.
"As far as they were concerned, it was only between them and their friends."
Then there is the question of methodology.
Even offline, there is no guarantee that a research topic is being completely honest.
On Facebook, it’s impossible to know which part of a user’s profile information and wall messages are true.
“What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things,” Selwyn says.
That’s why, despite his years as a technology researcher, Selwyn believes that a paperclip and a pen are still the best research tools no one can use.
“There’s no substitute for entering the real world and talking to real people,” he says.
“Social research is supposed to be about the social – and a lot of the social is still happening offline.”
"Cold and inhuman: Anders Behring Breivik makes his first public appearance in court
