7 Lessons from Steve Jobs’ Lost Interview Showed at a Theatre This Week
After Steve Jobs’ death on October 5, there were some who compared him to Henry Ford – distinguishing the genius of technology as the Great Modern Inventor.
But what Apple fans might find most revealing, in a recently rediscovered Jobs interview that has been dusted off as an advancement of a series of special screenings in major markets this week, is how much this creative mind understood about business processes and product workflows.
He was undoubtedly a self-recognized designer, dreamer, and hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer and a yonk of flowcharts — a man who believed many executives suffered “a disease consisting of thinking that a great idea is 90 percent of the work... [but] there’s a huge amount of work between a great idea and a great product.”
In 1995, Bob Cringely was developing the TV series The Triumph of the Nerds about the dawn of the personal computer, and sat for more than an hour with Jobs for a lengthy and rare conversation.
At that time it had been barely 10 years since Jobs had been forced to leave Apple, and he was already working intensively at his new computer company NeXT, awaiting popular adoption of the Internet.
While a small portion of Cringely’s interview was used in Nerds, he said the originals of the interview disappeared during their transportation.
It was only after Jobs’ death that a full copy was discovered on VHS in the director’s garage.
This archive material, slightly re-edited, is the basis for Steve Jobs: The Lost 68-minute interview, which arrives at Landmark cinemas on Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known to hate in-depth interviews, Jobs here seems surprisingly willing to expose his technological philosophies and business strategies.
And very thoughtful.
At four different points throughout the interview, there are great silences between the questions and the answers – from 10 to 15 seconds of reflection, where Jobs is clearly weighing his thoughts, seeking precision.
There are also times when Jobs’ perfectionism comes to the surface, where he seems impatient due to Cringely’s questions, pushing him to move faster toward the most important topics or arguments.
Filmed before the era of Pixar, the iPod or the iPhone, there’s something strangely prophetic about The Lost Interview, when Jobs evaluates what he sees other companies do right and wrong, and offers his own vision of the future of computing.
One thing is to read posthumous assessments of Jobs’ career, but there’s something raw and inspiring about the Jobs we see here, the anxious dreamer on the verge of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
Not long after explaining everything in detail here, he went and did it.
A quick summary of seven notable sequences of The Lost Interview:
About how you learned to run a business:
“Over the years in business, I’ve always asked, ‘Why do you do things?’ and the answers you invariably give are, ‘Oh, that’s just the way it’s done.’
Nobody knows why he does what he does, in business nobody thinks about things very deeply.
That's what I found.
Jobs details his efforts to simplify Apple’s accounting.
Bewildered by the way costs were recorded – often starting with a “standard cost” that was in the eye of good coverage, and then adjusting to a “variable” – he developed an automated factory that assured that they could determine retail commercial costs.
The Pope's Joke:
Jobs narrates the "Blue Box" he himself built with Steve Wozniak - a device that allowed people to effectively hack the phone company and make long-distance calls for free.
It has been widely written about the device, but Jobs’ euphoria here in describing the Blue Box as an act of empowerment is contagious.
Describes how he and Wozniak tested the box using a public phone, making a call, and then connecting from one AT&T network to another, while creating a loop with as many satellites as possible.
“We were wrapping things around the world half a dozen times and yelling through the public phone and coming back a minute later to the public phone from the door next door,” Jobs says with a laugh.
“We were young and what we learned was that we could build something ourselves that could control billions of dollars in infrastructure around the world.”
The two of us, we didn’t know much, but we could build a little thing that could control a giant thing — it was an incredible lesson, and I don’t think Apple would ever have existed without it.
Jobs continues to describe a glorious joke that he and Wozniak nearly abandon, calling the Vatican through the Blue Box in the middle of the night and asking to talk to the Pope, while making his best imitation of Henry Kissinger.
As several members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to talk to the U.S. diplomat, the two burst into squabbles just before the Pope himself woke up to go answer the phone.
About falling in love with technology (and selling by phone with Bill Hewlett):
At the age of 12, hunting for spare parts to build a frequency meter, he searched for Bill Hewlett in the phone book and made a call to him.
Shortly after his 20-minute phone conversation, Jobs got a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
“That was a remarkable influence on me, it was the only company I had seen at that age and it formed my vision of what a company was and how well they treated their employees.”
Jobs later became one of HP's employees who visited the company's research laboratories in Palo Alto, where he saw "the first desktop computer ever made."
It was as big as a suitcase, it had a small cathode tube screen, and I fell in love with it.
I would get a trip to HP as a teenager and waste time with that machine and write programs for her.
About Improving Innovation:
At various points in the interview, Jobs talks about inventing new products on the go.
Soon in his career, as he devoted himself to selling a handful of motherboards, he was asked by a client if he could assemble the whole equipment.
Working with only 30 credit days, he had to figure out the assembly and delivery of the finished devices.
Later, while at Apple, he recalls the struggles he faced in the development of a computer mouse:
“I remember having dramatic arguments ... they yelled at me that it would take five years [to create a mouse that would cost $300], and I got tired and went out and found a designer.
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could build for $15 and that was totally reliable.
About big companies losing strength:
Long before he led Apple’s renaissance, Jobs prophetically predicted how many industry leaders would stumble upon his vision, and lose control of his market share.
“Tell me you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make better photocopiers and printers, and what?”
You have the monopoly of market share, so the company is no longer successful.
Sales and marketing departments increase success, so it is this kind of people who end up running the companies and the people in charge of the products are expelled from the forum for decision making.
The genius of the products that led to that position of monopoly rotted because of people who do not have the notion of good products vs. bad products - the knowledge of the necessary trade.
That's what happened at Xerox.
Xerox could have taken over the entire computer industry.
It could have been ten times its size, it could have been the Microsoft of the 90s...
They took the defeat of victory.
About innovation as an artistic expression:
“There’s a huge amount of work between a great idea and a great product... as the great idea evolves, changes and grows.”
You learn a lot about the subtleties of it.
There are sacrifices you have to make - some things you can't make the electrons do, the glass does them, the robots do them, the factories do them.
You have to keep 5,000 things in your brain - these concepts - adjust them all at once...
In the end, it all boils down to the taste – it boils down to trying to expose yourself to the best that a team of humans has done, and then trying to adapt those things to which you are doing.
Picasso said that good artists copy, great artists steal.
We have never been ashamed of stealing great ideas.
What partly made the Macintosh great was that the people who were working on it were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians, who were casually the best computer scientists in the world.
If it weren’t for computing, I might be doing wonderful things in other fields.
Scalia and Thomas Dinner with Health Care Law Rivals While Court Accepts Case
The day the Supreme Court met in private to examine the politically controversial issue of whether they would accept the challenge to President Obama’s health care law, two of his judges, Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas, were handcuffed at a law firm-sponsored dinner that will expose the case to the high court.
The occasion was last Thursday, when the nine judges met in a preliminary hearing to thoroughly examine the requests for review.
One of the cases in question was a lawsuit filed by 26 states challenging the total health care reform passed by Congress last year, a law that has been a war cry for conservative activists across the country.
The judges agreed to admit the lawsuit and, in fact, a historic five-and-a-half-hour allegation is expected by March, and the result will likely further cloud the 2012 presidential race, which will be at its peak when the court’s decision is known.
The lawyer who will appear in court and argue that the law should be discarded will likely be Paul Clement, who served as U.S. Attorney General during the George W. Bush administration.
Clement’s law firm, Bancroft PLLC, was one of nearly two dozen companies that helped sponsor the annual Federalist Society dinner, a group that has been dedicated to advocating conservative legal principles for many years.
Another firm that sponsored the dinner, Jones Day, represents one of the trade associations that challenged the law, the National Federation of Independent Businesses.
Another sponsor was pharmaceutical giant Pfizer Inc., which has a huge financial interest in the outcome of the litigation.
The dinner was held at a Washington hotel hours after the court’s preliminary hearing on the case.
Attendees included Mitch McConnell, the most prominent Republican in the Senate, and an outspoken opponent of the health care law.
The special guests at dinner? Scalia and Thomas.
It’s nothing new: The two judges have been attending Federalist Society events for years.
And it is not something that conflicts with ethical norms.
In fact, judges are exempt from the Code of Conduct that governs the actions of lower federal judges.
If they were not, they could be said to fall under the Canon Code 4C, which says: “A judge may attend events to raise funds from law-related and other organizations, although the judge may not be a speaker, an honorary guest, or appear on the program of such an event.”
However, the absolute proximity of Scalia and Thomas to two of the law firms in the case, as well as to a company with a huge financial interest, was enough to alarm ethics activists in the government.
“This impressive breach of ethics and indifference to the code goes against the lawsuits of several judges acquitted by the court by the same rules that apply to all federal judges,” said Bob Edgar, president of Common Cause.
"The judges were handcuffed at a gala fundraiser with lawyers who have cases pending in court."
Their appearance and attendance in fundraising for this event undermines any demand for impartiality, and is unacceptable.
Scalia and Thomas have shown little interest in criticism that they say mix court activity too easily with the agenda driven by groups like the Federalist Society.
And Thomas' wife, Ginni, is a prominent conservative activist.
On the other hand, conservatives argue that it is the magistrate Elena Kagan, who has an ethical problem, not Scalia and Thomas.
Kagan worked as the Obama administration’s attorney general when the first legal challenges to the law were filed in the court of first instance.
Her critics have pushed for Kagan to refrain from seeing the case, saying she was too involved in advocating the law for now to be impartial.
Kagan has not given any indication that he is going to do so.
Boeing Receives Record Order of $18 Billion
The airline Emirates orders 50 Boeing 777 double-aisle aircraft, with an option to 20 more.
Boeing also sells six Boeing Dreamliner aircraft to Oman Air, an operation valued at more than $1 billion.
Rarely is it news when a company gets an order of 50 units of its product.
But it’s a big deal when the company is the aircraft manufacturer Boeing Co. and the selling price for the 50 aircraft amounts to a record $18 billion.
It is as big as the place from where Boeing received the order: the Middle East, a growing gold mine of future aircraft orders.
In a study released on Monday, the Chicago company estimates that over the next 20 years airlines in the Middle East will need 2,520 aircraft worth $450 billion.
Boeing announced during the weekend its largest order in history for commercial jets for their value in dollars - 50 double-aisle Boeing 777 jets.
The successful order came from Emirates airline in Dubai.
The airline also has an option to buy 20 more aircraft, which would raise the total selling price to $26 billion, Boeing announced at the 2011 Dubai Air Show.
Then, on Monday, Boeing said Oman Air had ordered six Boeing 787-8s, the so-called Dreamliner, which boasts of fuel savings and spectacular passenger services.
The selling price for six of them is more than a billion dollars.
“This clearly has a huge positive effect for Boeing,” Morningstar analyst Neal Dihora said.
"The quality of these customers in particular is very strong."
Many Middle Eastern airlines are owned by their oil-producing nations.
Therefore, not only do they have the money to pay for the planes, but an increase in fuel prices – usually detrimental to airlines, because it is one of the highest costs – is not so detrimental, because the country is making money with the rise in oil price.
That’s important because they are less likely than other airlines to cancel or delay flight orders when fuel prices rise, Dihora said.
“They have natural protection,” he said.
The Emirates order solidifies Boeing’s leadership in the wide-body aircraft market and helps keep its competitor Airbus SAS’ attempt to invade its dominance with the A350 passenger aircraft at bay.
Boeing’s victory at the air show comes four months after Airbus said it would delay the debut of the largest A350, which competes directly with the 777-300ER.
It delayed the debut to add more momentum after customers demanded an increase in payload and range.
Boeing Co shares rose 1.5% to $67.94.
The sister of the president of Mexico, apparently defeated in the vote of Michoacán
Luisa María Calderón claims that the drug traffickers helped her opponent of the PRI, Fausto Vallejo, in the fight for governor.
President Felipe Calderón’s sister appears to have lost her candidacy for governor of Michoacán during the violent state election, and she said Monday that drug traffickers helped tilt the race in favor of one of her opponents.
