"We're all together in this."
“So anyone who can help Europe get out of the crisis is useful,” he told the Financial Times in an interview at the World Economic Forum in Mumbai.
"Asia can be protected to some extent, but it can't be immune."
"So if China and India can help, let it be by any means."
The European monetary union has been severely undermined by a sovereign debt crisis in recent months.
In recent days, Italy’s borrowing costs have skyrocketed dangerously and the prime ministers of Italy and Greece have resigned.
The current sovereign debt crisis in Europe has heightened fears that it could push the global economy into recession and has generated calls for major emerging economies to come together to help the eurozone find a solution.
Mr Nag predicted that any Asian support would be channelled through the IMF, but said bilateral assistance – such as the purchase of EU bailout fund bonds, the European Financial Stability Fund – offered greater negotiating power for Europe’s Asian partners.
Anand Sharma, India's Commerce Minister, said "India will do everything possible" to help the eurozone as its own economy was now suffering from falling exports and depletion of foreign capital inflows.
