Lee Howell, Managing Director of the World Economic Forum, also wondered why India’s reserves should be used to keep the many well-paid Greek public sector workers in jobs from poorly managed companies and loss-making companies such as railroads.
Nag said the eurozone crisis threatens with “important chain effects” across Asia.
The Asian Development Bank’s forecast of 7.5 percent economic growth in Asia for 2011/12 now faces “risks down” due to Europe’s threat.
He said vulnerable emerging markets needed to make “contingency plans” to protect themselves from a crisis and significant capital outflows from their economies.
Pentagon Serious Warnings About Possible Defense Cuts
Defense Secretary Leon Panetta warmed Congress on Monday, warning that upcoming automatic budget cuts could undermine national security and provoke a chained financial reaction from Pentagon corridors to Afghanistan’s battlefields to civilian assembly lines.
The Pentagon is already digging the $450 billion in cuts over the next decade, but now fears an additional $600 billion or more in cuts that may be imminent if Congress fails to reach an agreement on spending.
“The impact of these cuts would be devastating for the department,” Panetta said in a letter to Senators John McCain, a Republican from Arizona, and Lindsey Graham, a Republican from South Carolina.
He said Congress’ failure to reach an agreement on the budget and its consequence, the so-called “kidnapping,” would result in 23 percent global reductions and a halt to many new projects.
“Such a large cut, applied in this indiscriminate way, would make most of our naval and construction projects impossible to execute – you can’t buy three-quarters of a ship or building – and seriously damage other modernization efforts,” Panetta wrote to the senators.
“We would also be forced to remove many of our civilian officials involuntarily and, because the reduction would be imposed so quickly, it is almost certain that we would have to lay off civilians in order to meet the goal.”
“These changes would break the faith with those who maintain our army and seriously damage the good will.”
The cuts would eventually reach combat troops, Panetta said.
“While war-time funding in the accounts of Overseas Contingency Operations is not directly affected by the hijacking, war efforts would be adversely affected by severe disruptions in base budgets,” Panetta warned.
“The hiring of personnel would be reduced, which would lead to delays in contracts and oversight of the contract that supports the war.”
“The payroll would be reduced, resulting in delays in payments to suppliers in time of war, and legal and political support would be interrupted.”
The two senators had written to Panetta 10 days ago, asking for information on the possible impact of the automatic cuts on the Department of Defense.
“The consequence of a kidnapping in the Department of Defense would lead to a rapid decline of the United States as the world’s leading military power.”
"We are firmly against this draconian action," the senators said in a joint statement Monday afternoon when they published Panetta's letter.
“This is not a result with which one can live, and certainly not one that we should impose on ourselves.”
“The kidnapping is a threat to the interests of U.S. national security, and should not be allowed to happen.”
Whether Panetta’s letter and recent senators’ warnings will increase pressure for a budget commitment or intensify calls to exempt the Pentagon from cuts is yet to be seen.
Panetta has been increasingly frank about possible cuts, despite arriving at a job at the top of the Pentagon with years of budgeting experience in Congress and the White House and knowing that he was facing tough decisions.
At a press conference last week, the defense secretary painted a grim panorama of what might be ahead — an army with a shell, but not a core.
"It's a boat without sailors."
"It's a brigade without bullets."
"It's an air wing without enough trained pilots."
"It's a paper tiger, an army of barracks, buildings and bombs without enough soldiers trained to fulfill the mission," Panetta said in his opening remarks at the Pentagon.
“It’s a force that suffers from low morale, poor preparation and is unable to keep up with potential adversaries.”
"In fact, it invites aggression..."
In an appendix to his letters to McCain and Graham, Panetta lays out new details of how reductions “generate significant operational risks: delays in response time to crises, conflicts and disasters; severely limits our ability to be previously deployed and engaged around the world; and poses an unacceptable risk in future combat operations.”
And Panetta said some of the biggest defense projects could face the axe, including those that are already being tested and some only in the early stages of planning.
That list includes the F35 Joint Strike Fighter, a new planned bomber, the next-generation ballistic submarine, the new coastal combat ship, and the new ground combat vehicle that the Army and Navy need to replace, the Humvee.
Stopping the development and additional testing of the F35 could generate about $80 billion in savings over 10 years, but its supporters say it is the next vital step to improve and address potential threats from China and other rivals.
How to Detect a Lie
A look at the most recent headlines tells us how serious and ubiquitous deception and lies are in everyday life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy exchanging allegations of sexual harassment with several women; each party accuses the other of lying.
Pennsylvania State University administrators have been charged with perjury for allegedly concealing reports that a retired football coach was sexually assaulting children.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was “pilled” with an open microphone stating to US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is a liar.
Lying has destroyed races and convulsed countries.
New York congressman and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weiner made the ridiculous with his denials quickly repelled by the irrefutable test.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with violating campaign funding related to covering up an extramarital relationship.
And, again, no one who lived it will ever forget the media circus set off by President Bill Clinton by lying during his second term about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
Legends about the traps in school and university exams are widespread.
There have been instances where teachers have given exam answers to students in order to be better seen in their performance assessments.
Mentors who should be teaching otherwise are sending the message that lying and cheating are acceptable.
How much deception do we find?
On any given day, studies show that they can lie to you anywhere from 10 to 200 times.
Sure, many of those lies are pious lies.
Another study showed that strangers lied three times in the first 10 minutes of meeting each other.
Detecting lies, or “locating lies,” is an essential skill that we should all acquire, for both personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a board game similar to, for example, Charada, where the goal is to exclaim: “I have you,” deception detection is a branch of serious knowledge based on scientific data obtained over the past six decades at prestigious universities that conducted in-depth research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that the old myths about lying have been refuted.
The liars look into the eyes.
They don’t always chatter, babble, rubbish or worry.
Nor can it be concluded that liars are difficult to detect or unmask.
A trained lie detector can get to the truth by learning about the structure of the statement, microfacial expressions, question formation, and times.
I spent several years researching the scientific discoveries about deception in the vast and ever-emergent body of knowledge, and it was clear that deception detection is a modern technique that is easy to learn and helps you navigate our complex world – especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviews, or negotiation management.
Good liars have the ability to read well to others, making them feel comfortable, managing their own emotions, and intuitively feeling how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men say more "self-oriented lies," while women say more "other-oriented lies" -- usually to protect someone's feelings -- that married people lie less often to their partners than people who are not married do.
We also know that if you are perceived as an offender, others will feel less guilty by lying to you.
How do you know if someone is lying?
First, observe the usual behavior of the subject.
This is called "creating a baseline."
Helps provide benchmarks to then measure changes.
Observe the subject’s posture, laughter, and vocal characteristic.
It’s best to know if someone normally kicks all the time so as not to make unfair accusations when you see their feet kicking in the middle of the meeting.
Next, look for deceptive, verbal and nonverbal behavior groups.
Consider these behavioral groups as warning signs, not as proof of deception.
People who cheat can freeze the upper body as they try to remember their story, point their feet at the door, lean toward an exit, change their posture significantly, or exhibit a “post-interview exhaustion” — that exaggerated sigh of relief and change of posture once all the difficult questions are over.
Often interrogators falsely show that the interview has ended just to seek that post-interview relief.
Also pay attention to the subject’s vocabulary.
Scott Peterson put his leg to the bottom and used the time spent as he claimed his murdered wife was alive, launching a nationwide search for her.
People who cheat can also use a distance language: “I didn’t have sex with that woman...Ms. Lewinsky” or repeat a difficult question entirely.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "restrictive language" when answering a difficult question: "Well...to tell the truth...to what I know...to what I understand."
This makes the answer a perception rather than a fact and is often a warning sign.
There is no magic formula for detecting lies, but developing skills to discover deception is possible.
