Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome gives details of the air crash in which the Secretary of Government, Francisco Blake, and seven other people lost their lives.
The Secretariat for Communications and Transport (SCT) reported that the results cast on the accident in which the Secretary of the Government, Francisco Blake Mora, and seven others lost their lives, indicate that the helicopter crashed directly on the ground in complete structural integrity, without the pilot being able to attempt a forced landing.
During a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary of Communications and Transportation, mentioned that before taking off the aircraft, the pilot found that the weather conditions were suitable for flying.
"The elements that appear to indicate that the unit had several contacts with the ground, the blades had contact with trees at 25 meters where the unit lost the fuselage."
It also reported that the unit was designed for 19 people, so it had the necessary requirements to transport the personnel.
In addition, he said that research done in the impact area does not report the appearance of parts on the ground.
"In a search report that there are no parts or components of the ship elsewhere, the impact was presented structurally.
"The design of the helicopter was for 19 passengers, had adequate requirements to carry passengers.
The terrain has a seven-degree slope at the 30-degree slope.
For the time being, the secretary said that it is a priority to have the results as soon as possible; however, the investigation could last several months, even a year.
Gilberto López Meyer, Director General of Airports and Auxiliary Services, said that at the time of the impact, the Presidential Staff helicopter was operating at cruise speed and that this happened on a soft uphill terrain.
"This information strengthens the hypothesis of a normal cruise operation at the time of impact," he said.
At the press conference, TBS head Pérez Jácome listed six relevant elements in the research:
Visual flight:
According to aeronautical regulations, the flight was carried out under visual flight rules, this implies that the crew must have visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Meteorological conditions:
Reports at the AICM placed conditions suitable for takeoff, as the aircraft advanced towards the area bordering the DF and the State of Mexico, cloud layers were presented at low altitude.
Selected Routes:
Due to cloudy conditions, the crew may have searched for an area with lower elevation and greater visibility towards the Cuernavaca Valley.
Location of the impact.
The impact coordinates and the last record of the radar aircraft coincide, probably before the impact there was no loss of control or alteration in the flight trajectory.
Dispersion of aircraft debris in a reduced area:
The information available to date makes it possible to assume that the impact occurred in a straight and sideways trajectory.
The dispersion pattern of the aircraft remains allow us to assume that the helicopter impacted on the ground under conditions of structural integrity.
No evidence of fire or explosion has been detected:
At the site of the accident there is still no evidence on the remains of the ship of some kind of explosion or fire.
The latest research results indicate that he may have had multiple contacts with the field.
During the field work parts of the aircraft have been found at an elevation of 9,200 feet above the middle sea level, the terrain has a slope ranging from seven degrees to 30 degrees of inclination.
The photographs show the sequence in which it was predictably disarticulated along that route.
The information provides elements that appear to indicate that the helicopter may have had multiple impacts on the ground.
After thorough search in a wider area than the agreed site, around the accident, no scattered parts of the aircraft have been found, strengthening the presumption that the impact occurred under conditions of structural integrity.
MSS Announces Protocol to Find Obesity Gene
Social Security leads research to discover obesity gene in children and young people; it is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) announced that it is conducting research to discover the gene of obesity in children and young people, called the protocol 'Genetics of childhood and adolescence obesity', which will allow to have markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry of the Hospital of Specialties of the 21st Century National Medical Center, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was integrated.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Center for Advanced Research and Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The research invites the population, whether or not entitled to participate, to go to the participating sports units of the IMSS in the Valley of Mexico, where tests are carried out on children, every Saturday from 8:00 a.m.
He stressed that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (West Mexico State) and that since October 8, the activity is carried out in the Nezahualcóyolt Sports Unit (East Mexico State).
Once the goal of bringing together 500 or 600 minors is met, the study will continue at the Unidad Deportiva Independencia (south of the Federal District) and finally at the Unidad Deportiva Morelos (north of the Federal District).
He explained that the purpose of this research is to know the components and importance of genetics with respect to the development of obesity and to identify in Mexican children and young people risk factors to prevent the onset of chronic degenerative diseases.
On November 14, World Diabetes Day, he said the goal is to bring together 3,000 children and young people between the ages of six and 14, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the implementation of specific food questionnaires.
They will also be asked about physical activity and family history of diseases, with the purpose of avoiding risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
On Saturdays, anthropometric measurements (weight, size, waist circumference), blood pressure reading, determination of glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin levels and genetics are applied to all participants (the aim is to identify genes associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz López noted that this research is due to the concern of health professionals about the alarming weight gain in minors.
"The health surveys of 1999 and 2006 indicated that in just six years there was an increase, in the case of boys, of 77 percent in obesity, and of girls of 47 percent; in terms of overweight, there was also a dramatic rise," said the specialist of the IMSS.
He indicated that the justification for the search for markers is based on the fact that the population of the country differs from others due to its genetic history.
He reported that on average, the Mexican has 65 percent American Indian heritage, 30 percent European and five percent African and this condition is reflected in the genes associated with diabetes and excess weight.
He explained that, in general, the genetics of obesity translates into the inability to burn the excess energy that we consume (calories) and that is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for the participants is the comprehensive assessment of the children, which allows to detect if they have some degree of overweight or obesity.
Even, he said, the presence of dark-coloured folds (acantosis) in the neck and forearm, indicating the likelihood of you suffering from metabolic alterations and even prediabetes.
The information is handled confidentially, doctors hand it over in writing to the parents, who are explained each of the measurements and lifestyle changes they must make to prevent disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentarism, which is the lack of daily physical activity, staying sitting in front of the TV most of the day and using means of transport instead of walking short distances.
It is also due to the high calorie intake, i.e. the higher consumption of sugary drinks, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins and the genetics analyzed in this protocol.
UNAM asphalt would avoid bumps
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at UNAM, develops polymer-modified asphalts to produce a blend with better performance, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signals that sends the pavement were even met, it would not be necessary to repair about 200,000 chunks each rainy season in the Metropolitan Area of the Valley of Mexico, warned Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of the UNAM, who assured that if the process of construction is adequate, it would be necessary to reduce the number of chunks.
In his conference A technological opinion of the batches, dictated in the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, announced that the laboratory under his charge develops asphalts modified with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the weather is extremely hot, such as some northern cities, to improve their performance and, therefore, the formation of loops.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, some of high molecular weight, called asphalts, and others of low molecular weight, called maltens, which together give the floor its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of the asphalt consists in that at high temperatures, about 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees centigrade its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees centigrade it has an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes brittle, he added.
The above means that on the streets the strength of the asphalt is not uniform, but is being modified during the day according to environmental and temperature conditions, the specialist in chemical engineering warned.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered by flexible pavement, which consists of six layers of materials, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Among the most superficial layers is the asphalt folder, made up of small stones bathed in asphalt and then compacted.
Each of the stones that make up the folder, he pointed, is bathed with asphalt.
As vehicles pass through and efforts are generated, this allows the forces to spread very well on the pavement.
If it were modified asphalt they would spread even better, the chemical engineer said.
On the asphalt folder, he abounded, a last layer is placed called a tread folder, which is made of a fine stone material, i.e., a sand that is also bathed in asphalt.
As it is the layer that will be in contact with the rims of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical force than the asphalt folder and provide friction on the road.
Being the part of the pavement that will receive and disseminate the efforts, the treading folder also requires having the right thickness and the material from which it is made must be taken care of.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he said, because it significantly affects the performance of the asphalt folder.
When the soil becomes moist, the water diffuses into the interior of the folder and it is difficult to get out, this causes a softening of all layers of the pavement and, therefore, the formation of lumps.
In the process of forming a flap, he said, the first to wear is the rolling film and only then the asphalt folder is affected, but the damage does not occur instantly, but it is a process that should be attended to the first signals with appropriate maintenance programs.
The member of the National System of Researchers also explained that the vehicle load is another important factor in the formation of bumps and, therefore, the thickness of each of the layers of the pavement must always go in relation to the vehicle load and ensure that it is complied with, in order to avoid frequent formation of bumps.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still a lot to research and work on the asphalt, for example, asphalt emulsions, which in other countries are already even on the market and allow to repair the bulges easily and without the need to use high temperatures.
