This was the work of the carpenter who identified the body of Alfonso Cano
A Cali lophoscopist went down in history as the man who confirmed the death of "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials is key.
On November 4, a lophoscopist at the CTI in Cali went down in history as the man who confirmed the identity of the top FARC chief: "Alfonso Cano", through the clash of his fingerprints.
Of the seven lofoscopists working in the CTI section, that week was the turn of "availability" to Eliazar González, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been working in the area of judicial investigation for 21 years.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in municipalities of El Chocó, where he often had to intern for more than five days in the jungle to get to the place where the bodies were to be identified.
In 2000 he moved to the capital of the Valley and, after completing the corresponding courses, specialised in lophoscopy, which is the study of friction skin, i.e. palms of the hands and feet.
The week of the operation against alias Alfonso Cano Eliasar was warned to wear minimum clothing for three days.
Something big awaited him.
On Friday night, he left for Cauca on a helicopter from Palmira.
He knew that he had to identify two bodies and that one of them was suspected of being from the man who led the world’s oldest guerrilla, so he was asked to carry the decadent card of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
However, when he arrived with the research team at the site where the body was found, he did not recognize it for its physical appearance, as it was very different from what he had seen in the media.
He was beardless, dressed as a peasant in the area, without glasses and much slimmer.
But the fingerprints don't lie.
Accompanied by a Galtonian magnifying glass, ink, a transplanter and a flashlight, Eliazar compared the body’s fingerprints to those on the card.
His eye did not fail him: it was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, the man from Puerto Tejada was in charge of confirming to the Minister of Defense, Juan Carlos Pinzón, that he was the highest head of the FARC.
In Search of the Footprint
For a dactyloscopist of the Sijín de Cali, the recognition made by President Juan Manuel Santos to Eliazar González, at the press conference for the operation against "Cano", is very significant.
A lot of people don’t know our job.
Dactyloscopy is an exact science, without margin of error, which can become key in resolving crimes.
Apart from identifying corpses, lofoscopists support investigations into crimes such as theft and murder and confirm the identities of the captured persons.
When captured, many criminals present false bills or have no papers.
We take their fingerprints and look for them in the database.
The investigator said that in a case of theft, it was up to him to remove a piece of wall from a house, because in that place the thief had leaned his hand to take out a safe full of jewelry and money.
"The walls are difficult because they are not suitable surfaces to take out a fingerprint, but in that case we were able to get the fingerprint of the entire hand and identify the offender, who had been involved in different thefts," he recalled.
Footprints can also rule out or reaffirm suspects in homicide cases.
Recently, they found a dead man, with bottles of liquor around him.
The investigation determined that a relative could be suspected of the crime and, indeed, a fingerprint on the bottle matched.
Although this does not guarantee that he was the killer, it does place him at the scene of the crime.
A CTI fingerprinter explained that in the objects "fingerprints are taken with chemical or physical reagents."
When they appear, a transplanter or ribbon is used to lift them.
After this, the impressions are sent to the Asif, which is the criminal database, or to the Registrar.
“The problem is that there are still many undocumented Colombians,” said the CTI expert.
He clarified that not everything is as shown on the CSI television show.
Just as not everything that shines is gold, not everything that touches becomes an imprint.
However, if it can be used, if the respective batting is performed.
‘Indignated’ Challenges New York Authorities
Hundreds of protesters gathered outside Zuccotti Square to camp.
Much of it followed the eviction order and moved to a nearby paruqe.
Members of the Occupy Wall Street movement challenged New York authorities on Tuesday by trying to enter Manhattan Square again, under a court order, from where they were evicted early in the morning, and by trying to occupy another Great Apple Park.
Hundreds of protesters crowded in front of Zuccotti Square, where they wanted access thanks to a court order allowing the "indignated" to camp again on the site, while another part of the movement responded to the eviction by occupying a park further north of the city, where there have been new arrests.
“Our idea is that, if the court does not allow us to camp again in the square, we will settle somewhere else and continue the legal battle to return to Zuccotti, as well as through peaceful sit-ins and demonstrations,” said Mark Bray, a spokesman for the Occupy Wall Street movement.
Bray said the "indignated" response to the eviction of his camp personally dictated by New York Mayor Michael Bloomberg reached the courts, where Judge Lucy Billings issued an order prohibiting forced evacuation of the site and allowing protesters to remain encamped.
In addition, the "indignated" proceeded to occupy a new park located at the confluence of the central Canal Street and Sixth Avenue, very close to the entrance to the Holland Tunnel, which connects New York and New Jersey, and owned by the parish of Trinity Church.
At least for an hour they managed to occupy the place, but then the police came and proceeded to arrest some of the protesters, although Bray could not confirm the concrete figure, while he assured Efe that he saw several journalists who were also handcuffed.
The organization said that several hundred people had settled at that point, where a delegation of religious leaders had already displaced in support of members of the movement and had tried to mediate with the police.
Meanwhile, Zuccotti Square - which is a privately owned building - remains closed pending a court hearing scheduled for Tuesday in which the legality of the evacuation of this morning must be analyzed.
Some of the displaced protesters carried and distributed copies of that court order at this time and even handed them over to the officers guarding the square, which provoked "some small clashes," said Bray, who denounced that some officers had beaten the protesters.
The court order prohibits authorities from evicting members of Occupy Wall Street or enforcing “laws that were issued after the occupation began or forbidding protesters to return to the park with stores or other properties they used previously.”
Mayor Bloomberg told the press that, due to that court order, the city had suspended the reopening of the space to the public and the protesters, who he warned, however, that local laws do not allow them to reinstall with tents and sleeping bags.
The mayor personally defended the early-morning eviction of Zuccotti Square, an operation in which about 200 arrests were carried out and which was decided because the protesters were "violating the law".
Bloomberg explained that he gave the order to evacuate the square because it was becoming “a place where people would not come to protest, but to violate the laws and, in some cases, to harm other people,” as “some businesses had received threats” and neighbors feared “for their quality of life.”
"The eviction this morning was disgusting and shows that in the background Bloomberg is more interested in preserving the financial interests of American workers than those of American workers," the movement's spokesman added, accusing the mayor of "missing respect for freedom of expression."
Occupy Wall Street officials also said they plan to organize "big actions" for Thursday in collaboration with community organizations and trade unions, to commemorate the two-month-long protests, which began on September 17.
