Japan is reborn after the earthquake
GDP grows 1.5% thanks to domestic consumption and puts an end to the spiral of declines that began in March
Since last March, the Japanese economy has been paralyzed, still recovering from the devastating earthquake that became a nuclear crisis, the worst disaster the country has suffered since World War II.
The early estimates of the Tokyo government amounted to $300 billion in material losses, a blow that, despite the difficult global context, seems to have eased.
After three consecutive quarters of declines, the Gross Domestic Product data between July and September served to turn the page, definitively: GDP increased by 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and by 6% at an annualized rate.
The record in the second quarter - for the Japanese, the fiscal year begins in March 2012 - also represents the highest rate of growth since the period from January to March 2010.
The recovery is partly explained by the upsurge in the purchase of machinery to restore areas ravaged by the earthquake and the subsequent tsunami.
In fact, companies increased their investments by 1.1%, compared to the 0.9% drop in capital expenditures seen from January to March, the first recession after six months of uninterrupted ups.
However, the real revulsiveness of the Japanese economy is not based solely on the Keynesian impulse that invites to take advantage of crises to reinforce – or rebuild – infrastructures, to use deficiencies to grow from scratch.
Japan has awakened, above all, thanks to the evolution of domestic consumption, which currently accounts for 60% of Japanese GDP.
This variable increased by 1%, driven by increased spending on vehicles, travel and leisure activities.
The stigma of the yen
Tokyo has entrusted itself to the domestic market, when the yen - the Japanese currency - has become one of the "refugee values" chosen by investors fleeing the debt crisis in the eurozone and the turbulent US forecasts, a privilege that weighs like a slab in the accounts of exporting companies.
With a stronger currency, products are more expensive abroad, a serious setback for a country whose economic floating line is determined by the health of large tech groups.
Toyota or Sony, for example, flattened their weak results between July and September to the yen’s valuation.
As markets continue their siege of the periphery countries of the EU, the Yoshihiko Noda government does not lower its guard.
“We must be alert to the risks that persist, such as the deterioration of some foreign economies, the impact of the floods in Thailand and the rapid appreciation of the yen,” said Motohisa Furukawa, Secretary of State for Economic Policy.
And, indeed, the prospects are not encouraging.
The Organization for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) said most member countries showed clearer signs of economic slowdown in September.
The indicator that anticipates turning points in the world economy highlighted that major powers are slowing down.
As it fell four tenths to 100.4 points, compared to 100.8 in August.
The eurozone, even, was below the average, which is at level 100, rushing eight-tenths to 99.13 points.
Athens re-emerges in doubt
Papadimos says adjustments will be approved, but conservatives will not sign any written commitments
With peripheral risk premiums triggered and uncertainty reinstalled in the parquet floors, Greece continues to entangle itself in the maze leading to the exit of the great European debt crisis.
The feeling that the "consensus" of the new Hellenic transitional government comes more from the demands of Brussels than from a genuine conviction of the political forces begins to be confirmed with facts.
While the new prime minister, Lukas Papadimos, warned yesterday that there is no alternative to structural reforms and that the 100-day period agreed in his appointment may be short to implement them, the leader of the conservative New Democracy party, Antonis Samaras, assured that he will not support new austerity measures in any case and reiterated his demands for the new date.
"The main task of this Government is to implement the decisions of the October 26 summit," Papadimos said at the opening of a parliamentary debate that will culminate tomorrow with a vote of confidence to the new Executive.
A package of 24 programmes to boost employment, reform of the staff code and new measures against tax evasion will be the first initiatives.
However, Samaras' message does not clear the doubts about his position: "We have committed to help the transitional government, but we have not committed to anything else."
The conservative leader went a step further in his pulse to the EU and the IMF, the agencies that must unlock the 8 billion that Athens urgently needs, and made clear that he will not give his approval to any letter of commitment to complying with the adjustments.
But the European Commission, still shocked by the impact caused by the Papandreou referendum, reiterated yesterday that its demand is firm: it will not unblock the aid if the new government and the leaders of the main Hellenic parties do not sign "a written commitment without ambiguity and as soon as possible".
Economics spokesman Amadeu Altafaj said troika inspectors would return to Athens “very soon” to discuss with the new government “what it takes to pay the sixth instalment” of $8 billion, although there is no definitive date either.
The Greek maze still has thread for a while.
