Energy policy:
Facts are worth more than dogmas.
If there’s a topic that can’t be addressed with short-term considerations in mind or just thinking about emotions, it’s energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly influence the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is appropriate that an election meeting be the time to reflect on such issues and on the place of nuclear energy.
The debate will only be useful if it considers all the economic, social and environmental consequences of the options proposed.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, on rational data.
Now that we are 7 billion people on the planet, demographic evolution will involve doubling electricity demand by 2050, unless a huge portion of the world’s population is deprived of a vital element.
At the same time, the increasing scarcity of fossil resources will have to be alleviated to continue to produce electricity continuously, without forgetting the imperative need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to combat climate change, a topic that has disappeared from the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these parameters.
That is why Germany remains alone in its decision to give up nuclear energy.
This is not the case either of Belgium, which submits its own to the need to find a source capable of replacing it, or of Switzerland, which only aims to build state-of-the-art power plants.
On the other hand, Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to name a few examples, are moving forward with determination with their projects.
The United States, for its part, after Fukushima decided to add a unit to its park, resuming the construction of a power plant interrupted after the accident on Three Mile Island.
If the German model, based on renewable energies, is sometimes presented as an example, reality goes against such discourse.
The choice of Berlin is going to involve an increase in the price of electricity, a greater energy dependence on the increased need for imported gas, in particular from Russia, an increase in CO2 emissions by the construction of gas and coal plants.
In a few months, the harmful effects will be noticed.
We need to think about the case of Denmark.
European champion in the wind sector, from which it gets 30% of its electricity, is also one of the major users of coal and gas due to the intermittent wind; for this reason, its CO2 emissions and the price of its electricity are, respectively, 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
On the contrary, thanks to the constancy of our energy policy, our neighbors pay an electricity bill 40% higher than that of French households.
While in a globalised economy the cost of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and a guarantee of the maintenance of industrial utility in the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
For that reason, any significant reduction in nuclear energy would mean a sharp rise in the price of electricity, which would undermine the realism of the wonderful statements about the reindustrialization of our country and the defense of our purchasing power.
This is a price that the vast majority of French people refuse to pay and, in fact, they do not manifest in principle opposition to this type of energy, as surveys show.
Remember that the energy policy of our country has lost to building an industrial sector with 125,000 director jobs and 410,000 indirect jobs.
Widely export-oriented, it encompasses a galaxy of SMEs specializing in international markets and that can create non-delocalizable jobs.
If France decides to abandon nuclear power, it would mean the sacrifice of a large part of those SMEs and the loss of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>6 billion per year in French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
Which electrician would commission an EPR designed to run for sixty years, when the collapse of its manufacturer is planned?
To solve the equation of nuclear energy, one must admit that there is no miraculous source of electricity production, just as there is no diabolical source.
Areva’s development of low-carbon, nuclear and renewable solutions demonstrates the complementary nature of energy sources.
In the case of nuclear energy, it is essential to maintain the highest level of security.
In France, we have a security authority that exercises strict and transparent control over both existing power plants and the construction of Flamanville.
Our teams, of recognized professionalism, are also obsessed with safety.
In half a century, the nuclear sector has suffered three serious accidents.
Only one, that of Three Mile Island, occurred under normal operating conditions; it caused no consequences for either people or the environment.
In Chernobyl, the accident was due to the design of the reactor and unforgivable human failures.
In Fukushima, some people seem to forget that the accident was due to two natural disasters of unprecedented magnitude, which resulted in the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear sector will learn from this accident, as it did from the previous two.
Thanks to these advances and cooperation between the security authorities, and the French and German operators and builders, the EPR presents a design capable of resisting such phenomena.
While it is being studied by all the electrical actors who want to build a power plant, the interruption of its construction in Flamanville would be a great gift for the competitors of Areva and EDF, as it would leave them free to take the lead in the inevitable development of the nuclear sector.
It is indispensable and legitimate to seek the best energy options for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let the emotion, dogmas and partisan maneuvers dominate such an important debate for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Immigration, a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy implemented by Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from various points of view: the saturation of police, judicial and administrative services subjected to the policy of figures, the compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of "country of human rights" of France.
More recently, it is the administrative harassment of foreign students that has jumped to the headlines, with the Minister of the Interior (see the newspaper Libération of 23 May) proclaiming in the past that France "does not need foreign talents, workers or waiters".
However, it is rarely analyzed from an economic point of view.
The point is that, on this issue, there is quite a consensus between the left and the right.
In the case of the right, Jacques Chirac set the orientation by declaring in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem for a country that has nearly two million immigrant workers", while in the case of the left, the tone was set by Michel Rocard explaining that France "cannot take care of all the misery of the world" in 1990.
The only difference, the degree of generosity
In 2005, both the left and the right shared the fear of the invasion of the national territory by a multitude of Polish plumbers.
On both sides, immigrants are considered to be a burden to the French economy and society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity with which they act towards immigrants.
In his program, François Hollande is limited to including trivialities, indicating that co-development will allow to solve the “migration problem”.
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may prove cost-effective electorally, but economically it comes out very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in a recent paper that summarizes the most recent knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is a broad consensus among specialists on the positive impact of economic flows on migrant wages, and countries that re-increase wages.
Immigration constraints weaken growth and undermine employment.
Concerns about the impact of immigrants are based on the idea that they can replace national workers, particularly the low-skilled, by pressing for their wages to be reduced.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are more complementary than substitutes for national workers and mainly pursue professions in sectors where employment is lacking.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national workers and the most skilled in dynamic sectors where training does not meet the demand for staff.
A positive effect on wages
Just as a surgeon would have difficulty working in a country that lacks anesthesiologists, the complementarity between nationals and immigrants causes the arrival of the latter to have a positive impact on nationals’ wages and employment.
Given the above, Giovanni Peri calculated that a 1% increase in migration flows implies a rise in real long-term wages of between 0.6 and 0.9%.
And, regardless of the fact that the diversity that immigrants bring contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (there is a large proportion of naturalized American Nobel prizes and companies like Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Immigrants are also net contributors to social systems, as they contribute an average of 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The International Labour Organization calculates, for example, that in Germany an immigrant who arrives at the age of 30 will make a net contribution (revenue less expenditure) of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>150,000 to the average public budget throughout his life.
At the beginning of his term, Nicolas Sarkozy wanted to go looking for the missing growth points "with his teeth".
These teeth, which deterred immigrants, had exactly the opposite effect.
